<br>
You're exactly right.  While Gorlab and Co. by no means proved the AC soft cap beyond a shadow of a doubt.  They made a convincing enough argument that a lot of people, myself included, started looking for hit points over AC.  Some people did some parsing, a lot of other people pointed out flaws in their testing, a few more people did some parsing, we came up with what we thought would be a really good test of the softcap, which nobody ever performed.  A couple people claimed to have &quot;inside information&quot; from VI that the soft cap existed.  People speculated that there may be some level of AC that would help above that level, and that it might be related to the mobs or their ATK rating, but no testing whatsoever was ever done with this, or even could be done since we couldn't reach those levels of AC and didn't know anything about mob's ATK level.  <br>
<br>
We have pretty much stuck with these theories for the last few months.  We can speculate that it may be different with PoP, but we don't really know until somebody parses it.  <br>
<br>
My point is, as one of the people who participated heavily in the original AC soft cap discussions on this and other boards, the soft cap and our understanding of the effects of AC is a basic theory based on a very small amout of relatively unscientific testing and a lot of speculation.  We follow it because it's the best thing that we have, but to call even the existence of the AC soft cap a proven fact, let alone some of the inferences made about mob ATK level etc. is really pushing it.<br>
<br>
Saying &quot;soft cap&quot; or point of diminishing returns, or whatever you want to call it is just arguing semantics.  Don't worry about it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6629">Brutul Vilesilencer</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
