haha, thats an instant classic <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=phantron>Phantron</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/7/02 5:20:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2591.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: is there a new AC cap?</span><hr size=1> Whether there is a cap or not this is obviously not something you can notice visually.  If you put on 100 AC and suddenly mobs hit min 50% more often then everyone would've noticed this by now.  However this doesn't mean the effect isn't significant.  Just because you can't easily tell what 10% more mitigiation means doesn't mean it isn't there.  If you're expecting to put on AC and start seeing a whole ton of mins, or the reverse, lose 100 AC and expect to see a whole ton of maxs, you're looking at this wrong.  People at the high end worrying about caps are at a point where any improvements are marginal and not observeable by eyeballing.  If you just got Bloodfrenzy, you've improved your tanking ability because your riposte skill is 15% better, but of course you'll be seeing plenty of times where you didn't riposte.  But this doesn't mean the riposte mod is useless.  It's just not enough so you can see it.  Whatever effects AC has, if any, can only be tell by parsing, not by you looking at some numbers flashing at your screen.<br>
<br>
As for the 'AC depends on mob', that's also false.  Yes, if a mob has infinite attack or zero attack then your AC wouldn't matter, but there is no mob with infinite or zero attack.  Even if you've a mob landing max for 80% of the time against 2000 AC, this doesn't say anything about how useful AC is, because maybe he would've landed for max 100% of the time against 1300 AC, or maybe it's only 82%.  A lot of people got this 'AC doesn't matter on certain mobs' because back in Velious days, AoW would pretty much kill anyone if he gets a good two rounds in on you.  But this fails to account for how easily AoW can kill you in two rounds.  How often can AoW kill you in two rounds if you've 7K HP and 2000 AC?  What about 8K HP and 1300 AC?  If he's less likely to kill you with 7K and 2000 AC, then it's better to have that combination of stats, even though inevitably you'll see a round where you tell yourself, 'Another 1K HP and I'd have survived.', but what you don't know is that with 8K/1300AC on a lot of 2 rounds you'll be taking 1K more damage than the other combination.  You can't say AC doesn't matter until you've hard data from what happens without AC.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=90049">Phantron</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daxos92>Daxos92</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/7/02 2:52:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2591.topic&index=30>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: is there a new AC cap?</span><hr size=1> In the simplest demonstration I can come up with, each mob has a &quot;range&quot; of AC values that will have the most effect on mitigating its hits.<br>
<br>
The orc pawn in freeport has a very small range, say somewhere in the 0-100 range. Once you hit that 100 ac, adding more doesn't make much of a difference (since you've pretty much beaten his atk rating completely - the rest is just random numbers).<br>
<br>
Kobolds in Sol B.... I'm just making up numbers here as an example. Let's say that if you have 600 AC or less, you get maxed quite a lot, and adding AC up to that 600 point has hardly any effect. That's because the Kobold's range of &quot;effective&quot; mitigation (or the start of the steep section of the damage curve listed earlier) is right around 600. You can keep adding AC between 600 and 900 and notice some very nice effects from your AC, all the way up to the top of the curve, where adding more AC doesn't do much (since the kobold is min hitting much of the time, and it's just down to randoms).<br>
<br>
For the AoW? Who knows what his range is, no one is able to reach an AC high enough to plot out the curve. Maybe the effective range - the range where adding AC gives you the best results - against him is 1500-2200? There's just no way for us to know right now.<br>
<br>
I know these statements to be true, at least on the basic level. The way the code is implemented may be different, but just think about how your tanking ability has changed against the mobs you fight as you upgrade gear and level (or the second time through, with a high AC twink). Each mob is different, each has a certain stat (or set of stats) that determine where its &quot;opposing AC&quot; should be, for lack of a better term. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=443380" target="_blank">Daxos Valdorn</a><br>
55 Myrmidon<br>
